      <level>
        <content>
          <table uk:widths="7.41in">
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>What are the policy objectives of the action or intervention and the intended effects? </b>This is an enabling policy which aims to achieve a twofold effect. The first objective is to specify Ofgem as the heat network regulator and implement consumer protection organisations into the market. This is what is explicitly legislated within the Heat Networks (Market Framework) (Great Britain) Regulations 2025 and hence is what has been included in scope of this IA. However, the intended effects of this policy go further as these initial statutory instruments build a regulatory groundwork in the market in which future powers and rules (e.g. extra rights and powers, Step In protections and technical standards) can be introduced through further statutory instruments to ensure greater consumer protection. The regulation also encourages growth of the heat network market by improving consumer and producer confidence. </p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <table uk:widths="7.38in">
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>What policy options have been considered, including any alternatives to regulation? </b>There are two overarching options assessed in this IA, a continuation of existing market arrangements (Counterfactual) and establishing Ofgem as the heat network regulator alongside consumer protection organisations such as Citizens Advice. The preferred option is to establish Ofgem as the regulator for heat networks market and define the initial powers. To operate in the market, a heat network must be authorised, comply with authorisation conditions, and provide a guaranteed standard of performance. The details of these conditions are to be determined by Ofgem.</p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </content>
