                  <p class="ia-table-text">Monetised costs include the costs to establish and run the regulatory body and the associated costs to business to be compliant with regulatory requirements. Over a 30-year appraisal period, including growth of the market, the central costs for Ofgem to regulate the market are £348m (discounted) for developing and managing the regulatory regime and monitoring and reporting prices. The additional costs on heat network operators to be compliant is estimated to be £122.2m (discounted). This includes the administrative cost to heat network operators arising from compliance with the regulation (e.g., the cost of applications, familiarisation and dissemination, reporting). This also includes a cost to operators of increasing maintenance expenditure to ensure adherence with guaranteed standards of performance. Consumer protection organisations and the Energy Ombudsman have cumulative costs that are estimated to be £107m (discounted). Further details on these proposals are set out in the main body of the impact assessment. Additional costs of compensation payments for outages from operators to consumers is estimated at approximately £28m for 2026 (undiscounted) subject to policy development. However, this has been excluded from the net present social value (NPSV) calculation in line with Green Book guidance as these compensation payments are economic transfers. There is a distributional impact from these compensation payments in the cost incurred by heat network operators and the benefit gained by heat network consumers. We have therefore included transfer payments in the equivalent annual net direct cost to business (EANDCB) to capture the cost incurred by operators and reflect this distributional impact. </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text" />
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Changes from estimates provided in the heat networks regulation - consumer protection impact assessment are driven by: </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• Updated estimates for regulator set up and running costs, mainly increases in resource requirement for authorisation, digital and monitoring purposes</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• Improved understanding by organisations on the estimated costs for this policy</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• Refined assumptions in estimating the impact of guaranteed standards of performance and compensation</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• Inclusion of advice and advocacy costs for consumers in Scotland</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• Updated heat network operator, supplier and growth figures</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• Change in the scope of the IA to only include policy legislated within the Heat Networks Regulation 2025</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
