      <section eId="section_4">
        <heading>Executive Summary</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Executive Summary</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>1.</num>
          <content>
            <p>A heat network is a distribution system of insulated pipes that takes heat from a central source and delivers it to a building or persons in that building. Heat networks are a crucial aspect of the path towards the cost-effective decarbonisation of heat and achieving net zero by 2050. In the right circumstances, they can reduce bills, support local regeneration and can be a cost-effective way of reducing carbon emissions from heating. Heat networks have the potential to provide around 20%<authorialNote marker="4"><p> Independent Assessment: The UK’s Heat and Building Strategy, Climate Change Committee, Table 2.1, pp. 22, https://www.theccc.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/CCC-Independent-Assessment-The-UKs-Heat-and-Buildings-Strategy.pdf (March, 2022) </p></authorialNote> of the UK’s heat demand in a least-cost pathway to net-zero, up from 3% today<authorialNote marker="5"><p> https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/net-zero-strategy  </p></authorialNote>. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>2.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Relative to non-heat network customers, heat network customers do not have the same level of consumer protections. This can mean lower levels of transparency and quality of service, instances of disproportionately high pricing, and no mandatory compensation regime for outages. Heat network customers are also unable to change supplier, giving heat network operators monopoly power which reduces incentives to provide a high-quality service. In addition, unlike other utilities, heat network developers/owners lack the same rights and powers, which can make developing and operating a heat network more burdensome. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>3.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The Heat Network Market Framework (HNMF) aims to mitigate these issues by introducing greater consumer protections and drive forward the growth of the market by ensuring heat network developers have confidence in the market. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>4.</num>
          <content>
            <p>A previous consultation in 2020 sought feedback on policy options for regulating heat networks and an impact assessment (IA) was published alongside this. In 2022, a final stage impact assessment containing further analysis was published with primary legislation and was introduced through parliament as part of the Energy Bill (now Energy Act 2023). A second consultation on the Heat Networks Market Framework (HNMF) was then launched to seek further feedback on consumer protections and pricing ahead of secondary legislation. The Heat Networks (Market Framework) (Great Britain) Regulations 2025 are now being implemented as secondary legislation to give Ofgem regulatory powers within the heat network framework as well as implementing Citizens Advice, Consumer Scotland and the Energy Ombudsman for consumer advocacy and dispute resolution purposes. This impact assessment is being published alongside the introduction of this secondary legislation.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>5.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The proposed heat network regulatory arrangement is a quadripartite structure consisting of Ofgem as the core regulator, consumer advocacy bodies and the Energy Ombudsman as the independent dispute resolution body. Consumer advocacy bodies consist of Citizens Advice for England and Wales whereas Scotland’s consumer advocacy will be coordinated by Consumer Scotland. The Department of Energy Security and Net Zero (DESNZ) acknowledges that whilst there are regional differences in governing bodies, an equivalent level of service and protection will be provided for Heat Network consumers.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>6.</num>
          <content>
            <p>This IA focuses on introducing this quadripartite structure into the heat network market alongside some first stage regulations, as set out in the Heat Networks (Market Framework) (Great Britain) Regulations 2025. These initial regulations include the obligation for heat network operators to be authorised by Ofgem. Ofgem will also take over billing regulation as well as monitoring the market. The regulation also gives Ofgem powers to introduce guaranteed standards of performance which aim to improve the quality and reliability of heat network services. These regulations serve as an important first step in introducing secondary legislation and enabling further measures to be introduced into the market. Some of these measures have already been consulted on by DESNZ and hence only require secondary legislation to be laid to implement them. However, some measures will require DESNZ and Ofgem to conduct further consultations to finalise policy before implementation.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>7.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Where possible the impacts of the market framework regulation have been monetised. Across a 30-year appraisal period, under the central scenario, the total cost is £579m (discounted). The monetised benefit of introducing guaranteed standards of performance result in a total benefit of £565m (discounted) over the appraisal period. This leads to an NPSV of -£14m (rounded) for the regulation. The costs include the set-up and ongoing costs of the quadripartite regulatory structure (£455m), the cost to heat network operators in the form of familiarisation and compliance (£71m) and maintenance costs (£52M). Although having a negative NPSV, there are additional benefits from reduced consumer detriment, price transparency lowering operator’s prices and facilitating the growth of the market; however, it was not possible to monetise these with reasonable accuracy and therefore the benefits are likely to be higher than the monetised figure. There are also many future benefits expected from the future legislation this policy aims to enable, such as technical standards and decarbonisation, which are not included within this IA. Further detail of the analysis is explained in this impact assessment. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>8.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The estimated costs and benefits within this IA are dependent heavily on how Ofgem decide to implement the regulatory regime, so we have used sensitivity analysis to represent this uncertainty. There are also expected to be significant future benefits which could be enabled through the HNMF, ensuring consumers are protected as the market grows, although this will depend on how the proposed regulatory powers will be used by Ofgem and what future legislation is laid. In addition, there are more consultations planned for technical standards and Step In protections that will have IAs published alongside them which will bring further consumer protection and benefits. The main cost of HNMF is introducing Ofgem as the regulator and the main benefits come from legislation that protects consumers and gives heat network operators powers. This means that whilst the majority of costs to setting up this regulation have been included in this IA, there are many more future benefits to come from future regulation in this area.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_5">
        <heading>Problem under consideration</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Problem under consideration</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>9.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The heat network market currently has minimal regulation<authorialNote marker="6"><p> With the exception Heat Network (Metering and Billing) Regulations 2020 &lt;https://www.gov.uk/guidance/heat-networks&gt;</p></authorialNote> unlike other utilities such as gas and electricity. This means that currently heat network consumers do not benefit from the same levels of protection as gas and electricity consumers. Further to this, organisations involved in the development and operation of heat networks do not have the same rights and powers as their gas and electricity counterparts, despite both delivering similar and vital services. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>10.</num>
          <content>
            <p>A 2018 market study<authorialNote marker="7"><p> CMA Market Study on Heat Networks &lt;https://www.gov.uk/cma-cases/heat-networks-market-study&gt;</p></authorialNote> by the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) found that, though many heat network consumers are supplied heat at comparable consumer standards to the wider energy sector, a significant proportion experience poor service, such as 37% of heat network consumers experiencing a loss of heating in the previous 12 months compared to 24% of non-HN consumers. The report recommended that the sector should be regulated by a public-sector body which has statutory powers to set regulation, monitor compliance, and enforce against heat network operators that do not comply with the regulation. Subsequent research in the 2022 Heat Network Consumer and Operator Survey (HNCOS)<authorialNote marker="8"><p> https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/heat-network-consumer-and-operator-survey-2022</p></authorialNote> has shown that though some improvements have been made to service quality, there is still a discrepancy between heat networks and non-heat networks. HNCOS also shows discrepancies around heat network pricing; with a small number of heat networks charging high prices significantly above average.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>11.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The Department for Energy Security and Net Zero agrees with the findings of the CMA to regulate heat networks to ensure adequate protections for all heat network consumers, support market growth, and decarbonise at the required rate to meet our 2050 Net Zero target. Following the introduction of primary legislation for HNMF in the Energy Act, the government is now proposing to lay the Heat Networks (Market Framework) (Great Britain) Regulations 2025 to establish Ofgem, Citizens Advice, Consumer Scotland and the Energy Ombudsman in the heat network market. These statutory instruments are the first tranche of powers that will establish a regulatory framework for heat networks which protects consumers, improves standards, and drives forward the growth and decarbonisation of the heat networks market. Future statutory instruments and Ofgem will build upon these initial powers to generate further benefits for heat network customers, investment and decarbonisation that are not captured in this IA.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_6">
        <heading>Rationale for intervention</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Rationale for intervention</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>12.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Several market failures and barriers have been identified in the heat network market, which contribute to inefficiencies, drive poorer consumer outcomes and limit the deployment of heat networks to below the socially optimal level. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Monopolistic characteristics – </b>In the right circumstances, heat networks can offer the most cost-effective provision of heating and/or cooling. It is most efficient for one supplier to supply the market, or in this case, supply the heat to a pool of consumers. However, once connected it is often not possible or feasible for a customer to disconnect or be excluded. This could lead to instances where consumers face detriment and have little recourse to remedies, as the network is a natural monopoly. This may mean heat networks are able to provide poorer services and extract rents from consumers, above what is efficient and equitable. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Incentives – </b>In conjunction with the monopolistic characteristics, new heat networks are often developed by for-profit organisations without full representation of the future customers. The CMA’s market study suggested that developers could have an incentive to be myopic and try to minimise the up-front costs to the detriment of consumers; either through lowering standards or recovering additional costs through future consumer bills. Not for profit heat networks may also face incentives to provide low quality service and inefficient networks as they have the monopoly power to do so.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Coordination failure –</b><b> </b>Heat networks monopoly power may be strengthened through the lack of coordination from customers on a network. A lack of collective pressure on the operator to improve the pricing or service quality means that the supplier can continue to exploit consumers without an incentive for improvement. This is viewed as a secondary reason for intervention as the removal of this failure would not remove the networks monopoly power and poor outcomes could still occur.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Information Failures - </b>Heat network customers can often face incomplete information and a lack of transparency. When a customer joins a heat network, they often are unfamiliar with the heat network’s characteristics, which can prevent them from making informed decisions. Currently in the heat network market, pricing of heat is less transparent than in other sectors, hindering the ability of consumers to assess whether the price they are charged is fair.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Development/maintenance barriers - </b>Organisations involved with the development and maintenance of heat networks currently have fewer rights and powers, relative to other energy utilities. This can make building, maintaining, and expanding networks more challenging and burdensome. In-part, this could contribute to poorer service standards and a lower level of heat network deployment than would be socially optimal<i>. </i>Though measures to address this are not included in the direct scope of this impact assessment, this legislation will enable future measures such as extra right and powers through licensing to be designed.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Equity issues – </b>In comparison to other utility providers, heat network consumers are not given the same level of protection. This is compounded by the fact that networks tend to serve more older consumers<authorialNote marker="9"><p> Heat Network Consumer and Operator Survey 2022 https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/heat-network-consumer-and-operator-survey-2022</p></authorialNote>. This may mean heat network customers are disproportionately impacted by instances of consumer detriment, with little recourse to protection. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_7">
        <heading>Policy objective</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Policy objective</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>13.</num>
          <intro>
            <p>The statutory instruments being implemented alongside this IA have the objective of enabling the market to be regulated. The enabling of the heat network market framework gives the opportunity for these regulations and those that will come in the future to address these market failures:</p>
          </intro>
          <subparagraph>
            <content>
              <p>• <b>Consumer protection: </b>Ensure heat network consumers receive adequate levels of protection by implementing consumer protections against disproportionate prices and unreliable heat supply, as well as promoting transparency of information and ensuring equitable consumer bills. </p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <content>
              <p>• <b>Support growth: </b>Accelerate heat network deployment by providing statutory rights and powers which make it cheaper and quicker to build and expand heat networks. Growth of the heat network market has been identified by the Climate Change Committee as a key factor in decarbonising heat to meet net zero targets. </p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_8">
        <heading>Description of options</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Description of options</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>14.</num>
          <intro>
            <p>There are two overarching options assessed in this IA: a continuation of existing market arrangements (Option 0: Counterfactual) and establishing a heat network Regulator (Option 1 Preferred):</p>
          </intro>
          <subparagraph>
            <content>
              <p>• <b>Option 0: </b>(Counterfactual): Continuation of existing market arrangements. </p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <content>
              <p>• <b>Option 1:</b> (Preferred) Establish Ofgem as the heat networks regulator and define the required rights and powers. To operate in the market, a heat network must be authorised by Ofgem and adhere to guaranteed standards of performance. Require Citizens Advice and Consumer Scotland to provide advice and information for heat network customers and the Energy Ombudsman to provide a dispute resolution service.</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>15.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Several other approaches to regulation were considered in a previous consultation stage IA, with the equivalent of option 1 being retained as the preferred option. Consultation responses found Ofgem to be the preferred regulator and that a system of authorisation and licensing (to be implemented later) would work best for the variety of businesses operating in the heat network market. For simplicity only the two options listed above are discussed in the main body of this IA. Option 1 now represents the Heat Networks (Market Framework) (Great Britain) Regulations 2025 which will be laid alongside this IA. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_9">
        <heading>Non-Regulatory options</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Non-Regulatory options</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>16.</num>
          <content>
            <p>There are a few non-regulatory initiatives which partially address issues created by the heat networks market being unregulated. For example, the Heat Trust<authorialNote marker="10"><p> Heat Trust &lt; https://www.heattrust.org/ &gt;  </p></authorialNote>, which launched in November 2015, established a voluntary, industry-led consumer protection scheme for heat networks that guarantees quality of service standards for approximately 11% of heat network consumers. Separately, the Heat Networks Code of Practice<authorialNote marker="11"><p> Developed by the Chartered Institution of Building Services Engineers (CIBSE) and the Association for Decentralised Energy (ADE) &lt; https://www.cibse.org/knowledge/knowledge-items/detail?id=a0q3Y00000IMrmGQAT &gt;</p></authorialNote> (CP1), launched in 2015, defines minimum technical standards for the design and construction of heat networks. Although these are welcome initiatives, heat suppliers are under no obligation to join and/or comply.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>17.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The international comparison of heat network regulatory frameworks<authorialNote marker="12"><p> The International Review of Heat Network Market Frameworks by BEIS &lt; https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/863937/international-review-of-heat-network-market-frameworks.pdf &gt;</p></authorialNote> commissioned by the Department for Energy Security and Net Zero identified both regulated and unregulated regimes. The report highlights Germany and Finland as examples of largely unregulated regimes but notes that in both countries the competition authorities can step in on competition issues. In addition, unlike the UK there is a large proportion of state ownership within the market which may be a leading factor for the absence of regulation. The DESNZ market study also reviewed Denmark; the market is driven by a regulatory framework to enable competition with price transparency at its core. Denmark has provided full transparency, with the government publishing prices for each heat network company on an annual basis. The report suggested that an unregulated sector may not meet the needs and expectations of UK consumers and hence requires regulators and government to intervene to protect consumers where there is little or no competitive pressure.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>18.</num>
          <content>
            <p>When evaluating non-regulatory approaches, they were deemed not viable to achieve the policy objectives. As the requirements would not be enforceable, this approach would be unable to provide the required level of consumer protections and support to the industry. The limited number of heat network suppliers signed up to Heat Trust suggests that rules on consumer standards will need to be mandated to ensure those standards are achieved across the market. This view is supported by engagement with heat suppliers not registered with the Heat Trust. Without regulation, it would not be possible to provide heat network customers equivalent consumer protections, compared to those not on heat networks, such as domestic gas customers.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>19.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Furthermore, the CMA’s market study recommended that government should install a statutory regime whereby there is a sector regulator. This recommendation is supported by the government and is further reinforced by responses to both the CMA’s market study, and a previous Heat Networks Market Framework consultation<authorialNote marker="13"><p> The Heat Networks Market Framework Consultation &lt;https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/heat-networks-building-a-market-framework&gt;</p></authorialNote>. Therefore, non-regulatory options have not been considered further in this IA.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_10">
        <heading>Counterfactual</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Counterfactual</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>20.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Without these enabling statutory instruments, Ofgem cannot enter the market as the regulator, and neither would the aforementioned consumer protection organisations. The full heat network market framework cannot be realised without the introduction of these organisations as future regulations cannot be made without an established regulator in the system. Therefore, without this regulation the market remains unregulated and unable to strengthen consumer protection.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>21.</num>
          <content>
            <p>This means the counterfactual scenario is a continuation of existing arrangements where the heat network market is subject to Heat Network Metering and Billing Regulations (HNMBR). This regulation covers meter installation and billing transparency, but it has no scope to cover pricing issues, standards of performance or protection of vulnerable customers. The heat network market currently has limited self-regulation and industry standards, such as voluntary membership of Heat Trust and the industry led CP1 technical standards applying to some new builds. In the absence of future government action, it is likely these initiatives would continue and possibly grow. An indicative scenario of growth in voluntary Heat Trust membership forms the counterfactual for this IA, more details can be found in Annex A. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>22.</num>
          <content>
            <p>A continuation and possible expansion of voluntary initiatives is likely to be insufficient to remedy consumer detriment issues or satisfy the CMA’s recommendations. As a result, the CMA could still choose to launch a market investigation and use its order making powers to remedy some of the concerns directly. Whilst this would result in some issues being addressed, it is not expected to be the most efficient approach and would not address the more systemic issues faced in the market such as the different consumer protections between heat network and gas consumers.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>23.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Given the anticipated growth in the heat network market, if left unaddressed, there is a risk that consumer detriment could grow. In addition, heat network developers would continue to face the same issues when developing and maintaining heat networks if they continue to lack certain rights and powers due to be introduced by Ofgem. In the longer term, this could also act as a bottle neck to growth in the market, potentially limiting deployment.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_11">
        <heading>Option 1</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Option 1</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>24.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Under this option, Ofgem is established as the heat network regulator and is given the powers necessary to regulate the market, as set out below. The regulatory model for the heat network market is operators must apply for general authorisation. Under this option, new heat suppliers and heat network operators must apply to Ofgem to be authorised to operate in the market. Existing heat suppliers and heat network operators will be deemed authorised and required to register with Ofgem. An authorised entity will need to comply with consumer protection rules for domestic and microbusiness consumers under the HNMF. These consumer protection rules may be extended to other groups of non-domestic customers.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>25.</num>
          <content>
            <p>This option has been selected to reflect the structure of the heat network market and reduce unnecessary administrative burdens, whilst ensuring consumer protection. Table 1 provides an overview of the key regulatory powers associated with this secondary legislation.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <content>
            <p><b>Table 1 – summary of key regulatory powers</b></p>
