          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>26.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The above regulatory powers are specific to those being directly enabled by the current secondary legislation. However, having these first stage regulations brought in and Ofgem established within the market allows for future regulation. For example, technical standards, Step In protections and decarbonisation plans are only possible as a result of this regulation and hence this option extends further than just that listed in Table 1.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_12">
        <heading>Summary of preferred option and implementation plan</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Summary of preferred option and implementation plan</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>27.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The preferred option is to establish a Heat Networks Market Framework in legislation, with a heat network regulator being given powers to enforce regulatory requirements. The proposed approach is a quadripartite structure akin to the retail energy sector consisting of Ofgem as the core regulator, Citizens Advice and Consumer Scotland as the consumer advocacy body and the Energy Ombudsman as the independent dispute resolution body. We expect the four organisations to work collaboratively, to share expertise and market intelligence and to regulate the heat network market efficiently. The proposed roles and responsibilities are detailed in Table 2 below:</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <content>
            <p><b>Table 2 – proposed governance structure of the HNMF</b></p>
            <table uk:widths="1.67in 5.41in">
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Organisation</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Responsibility in the HNMF</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Ofgem</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Administering the authorisation regimes. Market monitoring, compliance, and the enforcement of consumer protection rules, including price transparency and interventions. Further responsibilities are anticipated relating to future measures outside of the scope of this impact assessment. These responsibilities will be covered in future consultation stage impact assessment.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Citizens Advice, Consumer Scotland</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Advocacy and advice for heat network customers. Administer an Extra Help Unit to support consumers in vulnerable circumstances. National awareness campaigns. Reporting systemic issues to the quadripartite group. The remit for Citizens Advice will be England and Wales. It is proposed Scottish heat network customers will receive advocacy and advice coordinated by Consumer Scotland.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Energy Ombudsman</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Provide domestic and micro business heat network consumers with access to its independent dispute resolution service. Work with regulated entities to advise on how to reduce volumes of complaints. Reporting systemic issues to the quadripartite group.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Office for Product Safety and Standards</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Responsible for the accuracy of meters used on heat networks. This may involve monitoring based on testing methodologies and checks against agreed accuracy standards. By performing this role, OPSS will improve the accuracy and reliability of heat meters, helping to ensure consumers are billed accurately and transparently for the heat they use.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Department for Energy Security and Net Zero</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">The Secretary of State acts as the policy sponsor working closely with Ofgem and providing the relevant powers for regulation.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>28.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Primary legislation has been implemented for the Heat Networks Market Framework through the Energy Act 2023. This establishes the role of Ofgem as the heat network regulator. No impacts were incurred from this primary legislation, as reflected in the primary legislation final stage impact assessment<authorialNote marker="14"><p> <a href="https://bills.parliament.uk/publications/47261/documents/2122"><u>https://bills.parliament.uk/publications/47261/documents/2122</u></a></p></authorialNote>. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>29.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The scope of secondary legislation is to introduce the above entities into the heat network market in which Ofgem will fulfil regulatory duties and monitor businesses. Heat network customers will be able to receive advice and advocacy from Citizens Advice, Consumer Scotland and the Energy Ombudsman (independent dispute resolution body). This secondary legislation will require heat networks to complete an authorisation process and comply with the conditions set out by Ofgem. Ofgem will also become responsible for monitoring prices in the market, increasing price transparency and taking over responsibility for some metering and billing regulation. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>30.</num>
          <content>
            <p>At this stage, the Heat Networks (Market Framework) (Great Britain) Regulations 2025 only provides the first stage of regulatory powers for Ofgem and hence the full benefit of the HNMF has not been fully realised. A further public consultation is planned to seek views on further elements of secondary legislation such as minimum technical standards and carbon emissions limits. An updated impact assessment will be published alongside this to show the expected impacts of these measures. These policies will then require statutory instruments to be laid before these can be introduced. Whilst the majority of the regulatory costs are captured in this IA, the full benefits will only be realised in later stages of regulation.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>31.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We are taking a flexible approach to regulation; this is particularly important given the nascent state of the heat network market and the growth and decarbonisation we expect to see out to 2050. Ofgem will have powers to amend conditions for authorisation. This means that as the market grows and evolves and Ofgem develops more experience of regulating the market, rules on consumer protection can be amended and supplemented to reflect market changes and increased regulatory knowledge.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>32.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The phasing in of aspects of the HNMF will also allow for the exploration of different approaches to regulation, in consultation with key stakeholders such as industry and consumer groups. Consumer protection rules will be developed and expanded over time to allow for flexibility and ensure regulation can take into consideration the development of the market and key learnings.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_13">
        <heading>Approach to analysis</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Approach to analysis</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>33.</num>
          <content>
            <p>To assess the impact of establishing a heat network regulator, a cost-benefit analysis has been undertaken. Not all costs and benefits were possible to monetise, and impacts have only been included for the measures included in this regulation. Further measures such as extra rights and powers, technical standards and others are due to be consulted on and legislated in later years, bringing further benefits to the heat network market framework. A further impact assessment is planned to be published alongside an additional consultation covering a wider scope.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>34.</num>
          <intro>
            <p>A monetised assessment has been completed for the following costs using a Standard Cost Model (SCM):</p>
          </intro>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Establishing Ofgem as the heat networks regulator and its running costs.</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Establishing consumer protection organisations and their running costs.</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Businesses complying with core elements of the regulation.</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Transfer payments incurred by heat network suppliers from the introduction of a compensation regime. As transfer payments these costs are not included in the NSPV but will be considered in the Equivalent Annual Net Direct Costs to Business (EANDCB)</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>35.</num>
          <intro>
            <p>A monetised assessment has also been completed for the following benefit:</p>
          </intro>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p> Reduction in the number of hours consumers face outages because of the compensation regime.</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>36.</num>
          <intro>
            <p>A <b>qualitative assessment</b> of the possible impacts of the proposed regulatory powers has also been included for the following sections below. This includes an indication of the scale of the issues the powers intend to address and discussion over where the likely cost and benefits could fall:</p>
          </intro>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Benefits of the policy for enabling growth of the market</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Benefits of consumer advice and advocacy</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Benefits of price transparency</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Benefits of this legislation enabling future legislation </p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>37.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Costs have been scaled up across the appraisal period based on the growth of the heat network market. The central figure of growth in heat supplied by heat networks is calculated based on predictions of the effects of all current and planned heat network policies. Heat network figures grow so that by the end of the appraisal period the average heat supplied per network converges to the average currently provided by district heat networks. Policies such as zoning could result in district heat networks dominating the market and hence a higher average heat deployment per network. A similar trend is predicted for heat suppliers and so this average heat supplied converges to the 95th percentile of current suppliers. High and low figures are also used for the total heat supplied; more details are provided in the sensitivity analysis section. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>38.</num>
          <content>
            <p>These costs are compared against the counterfactual scenario (Option 0). This provides an indication of the expected costs and benefits that arise from the preferred option. The impacts are considered over a 30-year appraisal period. The 30-year appraisal period has been used as Heat Networks are considered a long-living infrastructure lasting upwards of 30 years. The objective of the regulation is to facilitate a market structure that enables the decarbonisation of heat through heat networks, a 30-year appraisal period models the subsequent costs and benefits such as ongoing regulatory costs and improved standards, which are expected to be distributed through this period. By extending the period beyond the usual 10 years other Heat Network Market Impact Assessments have used, the model provides a long-term comprehensive evaluation of the impacts as well as creating alignment with the regulatory measures of other utilities. We find that all ongoing costs and benefits increase over the appraisal period due to the growth of the market. All monetised impacts are presented in 2023 prices and where specified are discounted in accordance with the HM Treasury Green Book<authorialNote marker="15"><p> Green book guidance on how to assess and evaluate policy <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-green-book-appraisal-and-evaluation-in-central-governent"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-green-book-appraisal-and-evaluation-in-central-governent</u></a></p><p /></authorialNote>. A 2024 base year has been used to reflect the timing of the final policy decision, ensuring the discounting adjustment is applied effectively.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_14">
        <heading>Estimated benefits</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Estimated benefits</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>39.</num>
          <content>
            <p>This secondary legislation gives Ofgem the powers set out above. However, the benefits of these, and future legislative powers, will depend on how Ofgem use them. For this IA, we can only discuss the impact of the specific legislation being brought in at this stage, but it is important to note that we expect Ofgem’s actions and future legislation will result in larger benefits. We expect that these future benefits will also have minimal costs, as the main cost of implementing Ofgem is included in this IA. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_15">
        <heading>Guaranteed Standard of Performance</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Guaranteed Standard of Performance</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>40.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The Heat Networks (Market Framework) (Great Britain) Regulations 2025 grants Ofgem the power to introduce guaranteed standards of performance which incentivise heat network operators to provide a reliable and robust service to consumers. Though this regulation does not introduce these standards directly, the implementation of the standards are an intended, and very likely, result of the legislation so have been captured in the analysis. Heat Trust members are already subject to guaranteed standards of performance, and we find Heat Trust customers to have significantly lower outages compared to other heat networks. Whilst the specifics of this policy are not finalised, it is expected that firms will have to make compensation payments to consumers for outages. This is intended to transfer some of the cost of outages from the consumers to suppliers. We believe this will incentivise firms to minimise outage frequency and length and improve customer experience, bringing the market in line with the gas and electricity market. Guaranteed standards of performance may also include other requirements, such as keeping appointments and resolving meter issues. However, the benefits of these additional requirements have not been quantified within this analysis. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>41.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The length and frequency of outages in the counterfactual ‘no compensation regime’ market has been estimated using data from the 2022 HNCOS and scaled up to the rest of the market. We have then used data from the voluntary scheme, the Heat Trust, to model the factual scenario of the market under a compensation regime. HNCOS finds customers to have an average of 40 hours of interruptions per year compared to Heat Trust networks which average only 19 hours per year. Scaled to the whole market, this results in an additional 10M hours a year of interruptions due to the poorer standards of non Heat Trust networks. There are other factors that are likely to lead to fewer outages from Heat Trust networks (eg Heat Trust memberships are only granted to networks that meet certain standards), hence the analysis assumes a 90% convergence to Heat Trust outage rates. More details on this are included within the sensitivity analysis section. This analysis only includes the effects of guaranteed standards of performance; it is important to note that, once technical standards are also introduced in later regulation, this will aid in reducing outages whilst helping firms to pay less in compensation.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>42.</num>
          <content>
            <p>As the details of the compensation regime that will accompany guaranteed standards of performance have not yet been set out, this analysis calculates the effect based on the current standards and compensation in comparable areas. Ofgem currently sets breach of guaranteed standards of performance compensation for energy suppliers at £30 for erroneous switches and delayed refund of credit balances. Suppliers are required to pay compensation automatically to the affected customer within 10 days of the breach occurring. If they fail to make the initial payment, they will be required to make a further payment of £30.<authorialNote marker="16"><p> https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/publications/three-suppliers-pay-total-ps8-million-relation-guaranteed-standards-performance-final-billing-compensation-failures</p></authorialNote> The compensation for outages per day set by the Heat Trust is £40<authorialNote marker="17"><p> https://heattrust.org/the-scheme-rules</p></authorialNote> This Impact Assessment assumes a £40 per day compensation level as a central estimate. Whilst this may not be the exact regime that Ofgem decide to use for heat networks, these figures are used as an estimate of the value of loss of heat and the level of transfer between business and customer. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>43.</num>
          <content>
            <p>From this analysis, it is estimated that the number of hours consumers will face an outage of heat and hot water will reduce by around 9 million annually. The value of a lost hour of heating is highly uncertain but, under our central assumption, we expect the annual benefits to come to around £19m (undiscounted) once the entire market has adopted the compensation regime and adjusted its behaviour, rising to £72m (undiscounted) by the final year of the appraisal period (2053). </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_16">
        <heading>Consumer benefit</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Consumer benefit</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>44.</num>
          <content>
            <p>One of the key purposes of the heat network market framework is to ensure consumer protection, especially given the monopolistic nature of the market. This secondary legislation will introduce Citizens Advice and Consumer Scotland into the market providing heat network customers the ability to seek advice and receive advocacy from the relevant consumer protection organisations. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>45.</num>
          <content>
            <p>There is often a lack of information for customers about heat networks and new customers are often unfamiliar with heat networks characteristics, resulting in customers making uninformed decisions. These consumer protection organisations will have an important role in disseminating relevant information so that customers are more informed about their rights and how their network works in order to reduce consumer detriment. It is difficult to quantify the impact of better-informed customers due to a lack of information on how much customers know already and to what extent customers will act on advice. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>46.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The Heat Network Consumer and Operator Survey 2022 found that only 39% of heat network customers who made a complaint were satisfied or very satisfied with how it was handled, compared to 48% of non-heat network customers. The survey also found that a lack of time, information and money were barriers to customers making complaints at all. These findings show the importance of consumer protection organisations in advocating for consumers and helping inform them on best practice when making complaints.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>47.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Citizens Advice also provides support to customers concerned that they have received inaccurate bills. As heat networks operate as monopolies, there is a risk to consumers that they will be exploited and charged incorrectly. Therefore, having an independent organisation will help customers seek advice on the accuracy of their bills and the correct action to take if an error has been made, ensuring consumer bills are equitable. Whilst Ofgem is responsible for monitoring aggregate prices in the market, Citizens Advice will protect consumers from individual bill errors, such as incorrect usage figures; this is especially important given the higher proportion of vulnerable customers on heat networks.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>48.</num>
          <content>
            <p>In the Citizens Advice impact report (2022-23)<authorialNote marker="18"><p> https://www.citizensadvice.org.uk/about-us/information/all-our-impact/</p></authorialNote>, they estimate their work, covering all household energy provision, to have delivered £16.3 million of expected income or financial gains to energy consumers who took action from their advice. However, the heat network market is much smaller than this and has many varying characteristics. For example, there are typically more vulnerable and uninformed households living on heat networks who may benefit more from this advice than the average population. This figure also covers some of the period in which the country was experiencing an energy crisis. Therefore, trying to extrapolate this figure to calculate the gain for heat network consumers would not provide a meaningful estimate. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>49.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The regulation also sets out conditions within the authorisation regime to ensure proper debt management to protect vulnerable customers. This will include heat network operators having to follow rules before installing prepayment meters or disconnecting heat due to issues with payment. This aims to prevent exploitation of vulnerable customers and maximise heat provision to households. The conditions will also improve customer billing clarity to help better inform customers and make it easier to identify if issues have been made. All these authorisation conditions help to reduce the chance of heat network operators abusing their power and damaging consumer outcomes. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_17">
        <heading>Growth of heat network market</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Growth of heat network market</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>50.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The heat network market framework is an enabling factor in the growth of heat networks for a variety of reasons. Having formal regulation in this monopolistic market is vital for business and consumer confidence. The protection of consumers against poor quality service, high prices and other exploitation will incentivise customers to want to connect to heat networks as the market grows. Increased confidence that households will want to connect to heat networks is a key factor in incentivising private investment into building networks. This increase in the likelihood of households connecting to a heat network improves operators expected returns on their investment and hence, their incentive to build heat networks, which will help grow the market as a result of the regulatory framework outlined in this IA. Due to a high level of uncertainty and a variety of other market reforms and subsidies in this area, it is not possible to provide a projected growth figure resulting from this secondary legislation. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>51.</num>
          <content>
            <p>This improvement to consumer and producer confidence increases the willingness to invest within the market. An increase in investment in heat networks could provide opportunities for greater innovation into better technologies which could improve the quality, efficiency or longevity of networks. Whilst not within the scope of this regulation, future IAs for technical standards regulation will look more in depth at the effect of growth on technical development and how regulation will also aid in these improvements.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>52.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The secondary legislation also has important implications for the realisation of heat network zoning. Increased confidence in the heat network market is vital for encouraging investment into designated zones by new and existing heat network companies. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>53.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Growth of the heat network market is an important part of the transition to low carbon heating. The Climate Change Committee has identified that 20% of heating should come from heat networks by 2050 to ensure a cost-effective transition to net zero<authorialNote marker="19"><p> Independent Assessment: The UK’s Heat and Building Strategy, Climate Change Committee, Table 2.1, pp. 22, https://www.theccc.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/CCC-Independent-Assessment-The-UKs-Heat-and-Buildings-Strategy.pdf (March, 2022)</p></authorialNote>. The majority of buildings currently connected to heat networks are flats in which alternative heating methods such as heat pumps would be unfeasible or expensive. Zoning policy considers in more detail the relative cost of different low carbon heating technologies; more details can be found within the zoning consultation impact assessment.<authorialNote marker="20"><p> https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/proposals-for-heat-network-zoning-2023</p></authorialNote></p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_18">
        <heading>Pricing policy</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Pricing policy</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>54.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Historically, the 2017 HNCS and the CMA market study both concluded that heat networks typically offer a lower or similar consumer cost in comparison to other forms of heating. The 2017 HNCS found that heat networks were around £100 cheaper per year on median average than non-heat networks. However, both studies also found evidence of high pricing for a significant minority of the market. There is a lack of pricing data since the energy crisis, but we do not expect this to significantly change the trend of heat network pricing. This lack of data also emphasises the need for price transparency so relevant parties can monitor and understand the impact of policies and external events on prices.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>55.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Heat network consumers are at greater risk of higher tariffs as they are not protected by the Ofgem domestic energy price cap, as operators purchase energy with commercial contracts. The importance of this has been emphasised by the recent rising wholesale energy costs, in which heat networks experienced commercial cost pressures that they had to pass on to consumers. The effect on consumers meant government had to intervene to provide support schemes to protect customers from these high prices.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>56.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Given these unfairly high prices, the lack of price cap protection and the fact heat network customers are not able to change tariffs, the priority of pricing policy will be to allow outlier pricing to be identified and discouraged. As part of the authorisation conditions for heat networks, operators will be required to disclose information relevant to the price paid by consumers. Ofgem will be responsible for the development of what information will be disclosed, however, it is anticipated basic pricing information will need to be reported, allowing networks with similar characteristics to be compared and to identify instances of disproportionate prices. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>57.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Transparency benefits</b>: Ofgem’s presence is expected to impact the pricing behaviour of heat network operators, as it allows them to be compared to others in the market and introduces the potential for Ofgem to investigate them. Furthermore, greater price transparency could allow operators to evaluate their prices relative to other networks, potentially leading to network operators reviewing their prices. Customers may also become better informed about price comparisons if Ofgem publish some of this data,<b> </b>which would help customers challenge suppliers if they feel they are being charged unfairly. In instances of high prices, this should benefit consumers by lowering bills and making them more affordable.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>58.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Transparency drawbacks</b>: An unintended consequence of increased transparency is that it could potentially lead to current and future heat networks anchoring their prices on or within these implied ranges. This could lead organisations to both decrease and increase prices charged. Although this effect could be mitigated through policy design, it would still lead to a situation where prices are assessed to be fair. In addition, respondents to a previous consultation suggested they were aware of instances of disproportionately low pricing where the revenues do not cover the costs of operating the networks. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>59.</num>
          <content>
            <p>How effective Ofgem will be at reducing these instances of disproportionate pricing is uncertain. This policy is also limited by a lack of understanding of why heat network prices may be high. It is difficult to distinguish between operators that are profiteering and those that have high cost/inefficient networks. More data is therefore required to inform Ofgem's approach to ensure insolvency risks and poor consumer outcomes are avoided.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>60.</num>
          <content>
            <p>In addition, it is important to note that a saving to consumers will represent forgone revenue to heat network operators. Therefore, it will be vital for Ofgem to build an understanding of what is driving these disproportionate prices. Where prices are charged above the efficient market price, there is a deadweight loss within the market. As the market moves to more efficient pricing, the deadweight loss of monopoly pricing is reduced, increasing overall welfare. There is an increase in consumer surplus which is generally larger than the decrease in producer surplus.  There is also a positive distributional impact, since the change in price represents a transfer from producers to consumers, and some of the consumers will be vulnerable.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>61.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Measuring the size of this benefit is very difficult due to a variety of factors including not knowing: accurate price information, the effects of price changes on heat demand and the marginal cost of suppliers. This lack of information means generating a figure to quantify this impact would be very unreliable. Even though we are unable to quantify this benefit, the significance of protecting consumers from unfair pricing and improving overall welfare in the market should not be overlooked.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_19">
        <heading>Future benefits</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Future benefits</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>62.</num>
          <content>
            <p>As these statutory instruments are to enable the market framework, there are a vast number of benefits that will be realised as Ofgem start to use more of their powers and more legislation is implemented. These future benefits are only possible with the introduction of Ofgem and consumer protection bodies into the heat network market. Therefore, without this initial regulation, the benefits listed below would be unachievable for heat networks. These benefits include but are not limited to:</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>63.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Extra rights and powers:</b> There are plans to introduce optional licenses which heat network operators will be able to apply to Ofgem for, allowing them to access extra rights and powers. However, this requires further consultation. Currently, heat networks, unlike other utilities (such as electricity, gas, and water), do not have statutory powers to carry out roadworks and other activities that are essential to the construction and maintenance of their networks. For example, utilities companies can excavate the roadway via a permit system, rather than applying for individual licenses for each individual excavation as is required of heat networks. This lack of powers prevents sector growth as it inhibits developers to build networks at scale or expand existing networks due to the extensive processes they must go through to be able to carry out an expansion or development. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>64.</num>
          <content>
            <p>While the extra rights and powers are anticipated to have benefits for both existing and new heat networks, it is expected that these will be of the most use for the development of new networks. This shows the importance of extra rights and powers as a key enabler in the heat network zoning policy. To attract businesses to invest in zones, firms need the certainty that licenses provided will allow them to carry out necessary works at a minimal administrative burden.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>65.</num>
          <content>
            <p>These extra rights and powers are expected to make developing and maintaining heat networks easier, which, in turn, could lead to additional costs associated with the development/maintenance of networks (for example, more frequent road disruptions). However, any additional costs would need to be balanced against the benefits of works being more efficient, less delayed, and the overarching benefits heat networks can bring. This makes the scale of the net impact difficult to estimate however there will be a significant positive impact to businesses and a long run positive impact for decarbonisation through the growth of heat networks.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>66.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Metering: </b>As Ofgem takes over some metering and billing regulation responsibilities, there is potential for changes to these regulations. Whilst changes are not imminently planned, there is a possibility that Ofgem will require improvements in the metering information provided to consumers, including the use of smart meters. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>67.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Currently, consumers in unmetered open class buildings have minimal ability to monitor their heat usage and are not billed based upon the amount of heat they use. This removes the ability and incentive for customers to monitor their heat usage. Individual metering would mean consumers can be charged based upon their heat usage, incentivising consumers to reduce their heat usage and see this reflected in lower bills. It would also aid operators to identify inefficiencies within the network which, once resolved, would lower water and energy use and provide a more reliable service. Moreover, metering provides more accurate usage information, allowing consumers to make more informed decisions about their usage, reinforcing their energy saving incentives. Meters have been shown in continental Europe to reduce heat consumption of heat networks, due to improved heat flow data and behavioural changes by customers<authorialNote marker="21"><p> Effects of individual metering and charging of heating and domestic hot water on energy consumption of buildings in temperate climates. J. Terés-Zubiaga (a)*, E. Pérez-Iribarren (a), I. González-Pino (a), J.M. Sala</p><p /></authorialNote>. Energy savings mean less fuel is used in generation, translating into bill savings, carbon savings, and air quality benefits. These bill savings positively impact consumers and carbon reductions have positive social impacts however the size of these will depend upon how reactive consumers are to increased information.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>68.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Technical standards and decarbonisation: A consultation on these policies is due in 2024 and will set out the expected impact in more detail however at this point we view that it will have a considerable impact.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_20">
        <heading>Estimated costs</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Estimated costs</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>69.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Costs for the impact of the Heat Networks (Market Framework) (Great Britain) Regulations 2025 have been estimated as well as for the counterfactual scenario. These costs pertain exclusively to the cost of establishing and maintaining a quadripartite regulatory system and the cost to business of being compliant with the requirements. An overview of the costs included is below. Full details on the assumptions used can be found in Annex A – Estimated Cost Assumptions.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_21">
        <heading>Heat supplier and operator costs</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Heat supplier and operator costs</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>70.</num>
          <intro>
            <p>Heat suppliers and operators are expected to incur costs associated with the requirements of the regulation. These are set out below:</p>
          </intro>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p><b>Familiarisation and dissemination</b> - Reading and understanding new regulatory requirements and guidance. This familiarisation is assumed to happen at a heat supplier level with dissemination at a heat network level.</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p><b>Authorisation application</b> – All new heat network operators in the scope of the regulation will be required to submit an authorisation application to Ofgem while existing networks at the time of regulation will be required to notify Ofgem with similar information.</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p><b>Reporting</b> – Reporting is expected to be a minimum requirement of the regulation to gather the information necessary to monitor and regulate the market. This is expected to take place at the heat network level and is assumed to not require new or specialist IT to complete. </p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p><b>Additional administrative costs</b> – There is expected to be some additional administrative requirements related to dealing with complaints from consumers and preparing the required documentation for audits. The aggregated cost across the market has been estimated, but in practice, these costs will only be borne by organisations subject to complaints and/or audits.</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>71.</num>
          <content>
            <p>There is an additional cost on heat network suppliers to improve standards to ensure compliance with guaranteed standards of performance. We assume that some heat networks currently have poorer customer service and response times due to lower levels of maintenance on their networks. We estimate that all networks across the sector should be spending around a total of £2.6M in maintenance expenditure but poor performing networks are spending below average. Given HNCOS outage figures are 50% worse than heat trust levels, we assume a 50% increase in relevant operating expenditure by poor performing networks should bring these networks in line with those already complying with heat trust standards. As explained in the benefits section on guaranteed standards of performance, we assume a 90% convergence to heat trust standards. This results in a total additional cost of £1.3M to underspending networks in the first year.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>72.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Heat network operators may also experience costs from the compensation regime and penalties. Heat networks must provide customers with a guaranteed standard of performance and will have to pay compensation to customers for outages on the network. Additionally, failure to provide information to Ofgem could result in penalty charges for heat networks. The size of these penalties is difficult to estimate as there is a lack of information on the number of networks that will fail to comply and the size of penalties that will be implemented. Both these costs have not been included within the NPSV as firms that comply with the regulation and standards will not be subject to these costs. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>73.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Following the release of Heat Network Metering and Billing 2022 statistics, the numbers of heat networks and suppliers used in this analysis has fallen. Therefore, we are predicting a lower cost to business compared to previous analysis as there are less businesses that will be affected by these regulatory costs. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>74.</num>
          <content>
            <p>These heat supplier and operator costs are likely to range significantly between supplier’s, dependent on the size of the heat network supplier and the extent of monitoring data they already collect. Smaller heat networks, such as those managed by a landlord, may not have an efficient method of collecting this data and hence will face higher costs from this process. More analysis and information on this are included within the small and micro business section of this IA. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>75.</num>
          <content>
            <p>There may be additional costs incurred by heat suppliers due to the need to address any compliance and enforcement issues raised by Ofgem. These costs have not been included as they are highly uncertain and would be avoidable through compliance with the requirements. Furthermore, there may be further regulatory requirements placed on heat networks which will be set out by Ofgem. The impacts of any additional requirements will be considered during the policy development and future secondary legislation impact assessments.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_22">
        <heading>Regulatory costs</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Regulatory costs</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>76.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The regulatory costs within this IA are set up and business-as-usual costs to Ofgem. The set-up costs will involve the creation of the regulatory framework as well as the systems to manage it, such as setting up a database and digital tool to receive and disseminate information to heat networks. It is assumed that these costs take place in the first year of the appraisal period. Ongoing costs include the costs of running the regulatory regime. These primarily include registering authorisations, monitoring the market, ensuring compliance of regulation and undertaking enforcement responsibilities.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>77.</num>
          <content>
            <p>In comparison to previous analysis, these regulatory costs have significantly increased within this IA. As the policy is now more refined and closer to implementation stage, Ofgem was able to update the expected costs to reflect these requirements. A main driver of these higher costs is an increased resource requirement for authorisation, increased digital costs and an increase in the assumed growth rate of the market. These are even higher in the first year of the policy being implemented to ensure the successful set up of systems and processing of all heat networks for the first time. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>78.</num>
          <content>
            <p>As the heat network market is currently mostly unregulated, there are high levels of uncertainty around the cost and resources required to implement and maintain this regulation. With these statutory instruments being the first stage of regulation, there is uncertainty around how these powers will be implemented and hence the extent of compliance burden on businesses and staff burden on Ofgem are also uncertain. This has been represented by a range of estimates for FTE requirements and costs used within sensitivity analysis.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>79.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Ofgem have represented higher levels of uncertainty into activities such as compliance and authorisation as it is not clearly defined how Ofgem will enact powers to undertake these activities. Ofgem have made some assumptions about the structure of authorisation to generate these cost figures, such as in the first year of regulation, Ofgem will be processing registrations from existing heat networks and applications for authorisation from new networks. Subsequently, only applications for the authorisation of new networks will be received. Existing network registration should be largely automated however will still generate some admin and assistance burden.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>80.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The legal costs that Ofgem will incur also have significant uncertainties as there isn’t a similar regulatory model to compare to and it is difficult to predict what issues may arise. These uncertainties also come from the previously mentioned issue of the full scope of the framework not yet being finalised.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_23">
        <heading>Consumer advocacy/advice costs</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Consumer advocacy/advice costs</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>81.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The expansion of consumer advocacy and advice organisations to provide information and help customers affected by heat networks increases resource burden and costs to these entities. This secondary legislation implements Citizens Advice to provide consumer advice and advocacy for England and Wales. Scotland will also provide consumer protection coordinated by Consumer Scotland. The Energy Ombudsman covers all of Great Britain and will act as dispute resolution between consumers and heat network operators. Due to the complex and uncertain nature of consumer advocacy and advice in Scotland, the IA calculates the total cost to these entities as a cumulative figure. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>82.</num>
          <content>
            <p>This IA is the first to include Scottish advocacy and advice costs within the analysis and hence this increases the total costs within this category. Citizens Advice are still predicting similar costs to previous analysis however the areas in which this resource is focused has changed. The Energy Ombudsman have seen increased cost predictions due to a higher reported complaints rate and increased customers on heat networks.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>83.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Ofgem and costs to business estimates account for the implementation timeframe and anticipated growth in the market. This has been done by phasing in the costs associated with regulatory activities and therefore the associated resource. To account for the anticipated growth in the market, aspects of these costs have been scaled in line with the anticipated growth across the appraisal period. The details on this analysis can be found in Annex A – Estimated Cost Assumptions.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>84.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Consumer Scotland are still in the process of scoping the extent of resource required to fulfil their legislative obligation. Therefore, these figures have high levels of uncertainty around them and may not fully represent what resource will be needed once the regulation comes into effect. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_24">
        <heading>Counterfactual</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Counterfactual</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>85.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The estimated counterfactual costs assume the continuation and growth of voluntary market arrangements. To estimate this, we have forecasted Heat Trust membership over a 30-year appraisal period based on the growth in membership over the last 7 years<authorialNote marker="22"><p> Based on the annual reports from the Heat Trust &lt; https://heattrust.org/annual-reports-v2</p></authorialNote>, and in the central case this leads to around 288,000 customers covered by the Heat Trust by the end of the appraisal period. Heat Trust membership fees have been applied to estimate the total running costs of the scheme. There are no set up costs included as these are sunk costs. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>86.</num>
          <content>
            <p>There are also expected to be costs to business in the counterfactual. All the costs to business have been adjusted to reflect the current requirements of Heat Trust membership and only apply to the networks which are members of the Heat Trust. In addition, we have included the costs associated with the 4-year reporting that all networks are required to submit as part of the heat network metering and billing notifications. Please see Annex A – Estimated Cost Assumptions for more details. </p>
