            <p><b>Annex</b></p>
            <p>A – Estimated Cost Assumptions </p>
            <p>This annex outlines the assumptions behind the estimated regulator costs, cost to business and the counterfactual. </p>
            <p><b>Regulation Cost Estimate </b></p>
            <p>Below is an overview of the approach taken to estimate regulatory costs. This approach is consistent with the approach taken in the recent consultation, where full details can be found in the technical annex of the consultation. </p>
            <p>A standard cost model approach has been used to estimate the regulatory costs of the preferred option. An overview of the methodology used is as follows: </p>
            <blockContainer>
              <num><b>A)</b></num>
              <p><b>Current market </b>- The current size of the heat network market in scope of regulation was estimated using the HNMBR notification data. There is uncertainty in this data about the current size of the market, with a risk that a significant number of small networks are not captured. The impact of the size of the market has been tested through analysis of the growth rate, explained in section C. </p>
            </blockContainer>
            <blockContainer>
              <num><b>B)</b></num>
              <p><b>Identify regulatory activities and estimate the resource </b>- The members of the quadripartite group used the outputs on market size from step A to estimate a range of required resource, which have been used as the key inputs to this cost modelling. This includes the number of full-time equivalent (FTE) staff by seniority, consultancy, and overhead costs. These estimates were then further refined following scrutiny from the Department for Energy Security and Net Zero and key stakeholders including industry and other regulatory bodies. The ONS statistics use average Civil Service pay to calculate the cost of the required FTE. These costs were then inflated by 21.8% to account for non-wage costs, in line with RPC guidance.</p>
            </blockContainer>
            <blockContainer>
              <num><b>C)</b></num>
              <p><b>Profile and scale resource requirements </b>– To account for the anticipated growth, illustrative annual growth rates have been constructed based on the available evidence, detailed in Table 5. Sensitivity testing has shown that the future growth rate of the market plays a much larger role in the conclusions of the analysis than the estimate for the current size of the market. </p>
            </blockContainer>
